  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Humanitarian Assistance to Conflict Affected Households in Greater Upper Nile, South Sudan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">With the lull in national-level hostilities that has accompanied the Revitalized Agreement for the Resolution of Conflict in South Sudan (R-ARCSS), displaced populations have begun returning from former UN Protection of Civilian and IDP sites, as well as host-community settings, and refugee settlements in neighbouring countries, with an estimated 1,101,543 returnees since the signing of the Agreement. However, protracted conflict, underdevelopment, climate-related shocks, hyperinflation, and unemployment have eroded livelihoods and coping strategies, and precluded communities from fully recovering from effects of war. Through this project, IOM is focusing its efforts around three interlinked and mutually reinforcing outcomes. The dignity and living conditions of IDPs residing in IDP sites is ensured through appropriate and timely service provision. Communities in areas of return, and hard-to-reach and underserved areas, have strengthened access to key services through rapid and mobile response mechanisms, institutional strengthening, and resilience efforts. Enhance service delivery across South Sudan through strengthened coordination, protection mainstreaming, and provision of enabling services for the wider humanitarian community.</narrative>
  </description>
